==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: nine
<hw>nine</hw> <pr>(n⟦imac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>nine</ets>, <ets>nihen</ets>, AS. <ets>nigon</ets>,
<ets>nigan</ets>; akin to D. & LG. <ets>negen</ets>, OS. & OFries.
<ets>nigun</ets>, OHG. <ets>niun</ets>, G. <ets>neun</ets>, Icel.
<ets>n⟦imac⟧u</ets>, sw. <ets>nio</ets>, Dan. <ets>ni</ets>, Goth.
<ets>niun</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>naoi</ets>, W. <ets>naw</ets>, L.
<ets>novem</ets>, Gr. <grk>'enne`a</grk>, Skr. <ets>navan</ets>; of
unknown origin. ⟦root⟧307. Cf. <er>Novembeer</er>.]</ety> <def>Eight and
one more; one less than ten; <as>as, <ex>nine</ex> miles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nine men's morris</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Morris</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Nine points circle</b></col>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>a circle so related to any given triangle as to
pass through the three points in which the perpendiculars from the
angles of the triangle upon the opposite sides (or the sides produced)
meet the sides. It also passes through the three middle points of the
sides of the triangle and through the three middle points of those parts
of the perpendiculars that are between their common point of meeting and
the angles of the triangle. The circle is hence called the <altname>nine
points circle</altname> or <altname>six points
circle</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nine
<hw>Nine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The number greater than
eight by a unit; nine units or objects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A symbol representing nine units, as 9 or
ix.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A group of nine people; <as>as, the New York
<ex>nine</ex> (a baseball team)</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Nine</b></col>, <cd>the nine Muses.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nine-bark</ent>⟦br⟧
